article.headline: Rebound specialist Snow goes on offense
article.linkText: Snow's split-second layup ends Liberty's streak
article.story:
NEW YORK (AP) -- Michelle Snow knew what she had to do when she
got the ball with the score tied and time running out.

Snow grabbed the rebound of Janeth Arcain's missed shot and hit
a layup with 0.3 seconds left to cap Houston's 15-point second-half
comeback and lift the Comets to a 71-69 victory over the New York
Liberty on Wednesday night.

"My role on this team is to rebound and put the ball up," Snow
said. "There's no bigger clutch situation than the one that was
out there -- to get a rebound and put it up and give your team a
chance at winning."

Sheryl Swoopes scored 21 points, Tina Thompson had 17, Arcain 13
and Snow 10 for the Comets (14-9), who trailed 45-30 in the opening
minute of the second half.

"We drew the play for Janeth Arcain," Comets coach Van
Chancellor said. "There was a little scramble there, and that was
a big-time rebound for us. We won the game coming back by playing
great defense, finally finding a way to shut them down defensively.
Not shut them down, stop them a little bit."

Becky Hammon had 15 points and Ann Wauters added 11 for the
Liberty (11-10), who had their three-game win streak snapped.
Shameka Christon missed a potential tying alley-oop on an inbounds
pass as time expired.

"We take that shot in practice," Liberty coach Pat Coyle said.
"Ninety-nine percent of the time, that shot drops. Tonight it
didn't."

A basket by Arcain cut Houston's deficit to 63-59 with 5:17
remaining, and she made it 65-62 nearly two minutes later.

Crystal Robinson's jumper pushed New York's lead to five with
2:52 left. However, Thompson hit a hook shot and Swoopes made a
fastbreak layup to cut Houston's deficit to 67-66 with 1:20 left.
After Christon's basket increased the Liberty's advantage to three,
Swoopes tied it with a three-point play with 47 seconds left.

The Comets outrebounded New York 28-23 and had 11 offensive
boards.

"We didn't box out enough, but our effort was definitely
there," Coyle said. "There are no cupcakes in this league -- not
anymore. You have to come out every night and battle, make every
possession count. We had a chance to win it. They made the plays,
we didn't."

Wauters made two free throws 47 seconds into the second half to
stretch New York's lead to 45-30 before Houston began slowly
chipping away.

"I'm a bit stunned that we lost this game," Hammon said. "We
played a great 20 minutes in the first half. But as great as we
played, we played that badly in the second half."

Thompson's basket with 14:59 left capped a 12-6 run and cut the
Comets' deficit to 49-42. Swoopes made a pair of free throws with
8:50 left to make it 56-50.

Christon drove to the basket, twice missed layups and grabbed
the rebounds before converting her third try to make it 60-53 with
just over 7½ minutes left.

Thompson, playing just her fourth game of the season after
giving birth in May, averaged just five points in her first three.

"It's good to have Tina Thompson back," Chancellor said.
"That's the best she's played."

After shooting 72 percent (18-for-25) in the first half, New
York was just 8-of-23 (35 percent) after the break.

"In the first half, they were about as good as I've ever seen
offensively in the WNBA," Chancellor said.

The teams traded baskets for the first six minutes before the
Liberty took control with 10-0 run, capped by La'Keshia Frett's
layup that made it 27-16 with 9:35 remaining. Frett had the last
six points of that stretch.

Hammon's driving layup with 2:04 left gave New York its biggest
lead at 41-25.

The Comets scored five straight points to cut the deficit to 11,
but Frett's reverse with 20.5 seconds left gave the Liberty a 43-30
lead at the break.

"I told everybody we should be embarrassed to come in here at
halftime and allow any team (to) shoot 72 percent," Swoopes said.
"Our defense basically didn't exist. They kind of did whatever
they wanted to do."

Houston's Tari Phillips got nice ovation from the crowd when she
entered the game with just under five minutes to go in the first
half. Phillips spent five seasons with the Liberty before signing
with the Comets in the offseason.

"The support I've had in the years here, I really am thankful
for that," Phillips said. "Walking down the street and coming
into the building, everyone extending their salute and 'We love
you,' that means a lot to me."
